Explain the assumptions of the model

The model allows to makes the 4 main assumptions:

  • Linear relationship: The explanatory variable X and the dependent variable Y show a linear relationship.
  • independence of residuals: The residuals should be independent. -normal distribution of residuals : the observations look normally distributed around the fitted line
  • Equal variance of residuals: the distance between observations from the fitted line should be the same on the left and right sides

Interpret the validity of those assumptions based on the diagnostic plots

  • Linear relationship: We observe a linear relationship between the variable X and Y according to the plot of residuals VS fitted values .
  • independence of residuals: Observations are independent of each other.
  • normal distribution of residuals : the observations look normally distributed according to the Q-Q plot
  • Equal variance of residuals: the variance of the residual is the same for each value of the dependent variable,indicating that the data is in homoscedasticity.

For address, “urban” area had a negative coefficient which indicate a decrease of the odd ratio for address of students. The odds ratio of 2.52 for sex “Male” indicates that the odds of high alcohol use for males are approximately 2.52 times higher than for females.

## the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  graphics::arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

  mutate(baseline = RATS$WD1)

fit <- lm(mean~baseline+Group, data = RATSL8S2)

# Compute the analysis of variance table for the fitted model with anova()
anova(fit)

## Response: mean
##           Df Sum Sq Mean Sq   F value   Pr(>F)    
## baseline   1 253625  253625 1859.8201 1.57e-14 ***
## Group      2    879     439    3.2219  0.07586 .  
## Residuals 12   1636     136                       
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The anova test results show a significant difference between at least 2 groups.

Baseline measurements of the outcome variable in a longitudinal study are often correlated with the chosen summary measure and using such measures in the analysis can often lead to substantial gains in precision when used appropriately as a covariate in an analysis of covariance. We can illustrate the analysis on the data using the WD value corresponding to time zero taken prior to the start of treatment as the baseline covariate. We see that the baseline WD is strongly related to the WD values taken after treatment has begun, but there is still no evidence of a treatment difference even after conditioning on the baseline value.
